Re: Insults veiled as "cheering"

It's not cool, it never has been. I called this out at majors in the past, and certain communities dogpiled me for asking people to cool it with the language in earshot of families with kids

Being disrespectful is not a "culture"

When you make people feel uncomfortable they don't want to come back. They tell their friends about their experience and their friends don't want to go either

By telling a guest to "die" you told an entire country you're not welcome at our events

People need to realize that their individual actions have sweeping consequences for the group(s) they represent. It's never just "[individual] did this," it's "[community] did this"

It's not the fault of one person, it's the fault of the community who allowed it to happen
